ON 7/11/00 AT 0700 TRAILER 8515 ARRIVED AT JACKSON, TN FROM ATLANTA, GA. UPON OPENING OF THE TRAILER 2 DRUMS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID (UN1805) HAD SHIFTED OFF A PALLET AND TURNED OVER WITH APPROXIMATELY 10 OZ OF THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED FROM AROUND THE LIDS ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  WE FOLLOWED INSTRUCTIONS ACCORDING TO ERG BOOK AND NOTIFIED AAA COOPER TRANSPORTATION HDRM DEPARTMENT AND SPOKE WITH ALAN LOVE ABOUT THE PROPER CLEANUP PROCEDURE WHICH WAS TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED CORROSIVE LIQUID WITH SODA ASH.  ALL AAA COOPER TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEES ARE TRAINED IN THE PROPER HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RE: (HM 181) AS WELL AS DOCKMEN ARE TRAINED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURE OF LOADING DRUMS RE: (DOCK TRAINING MANUAL VII A.)  THE DRUMS SHOULD HAVE BEEN PROPERLY SECURED WITH DUNNAGE AND NECESSARY MEAN TO KEEP THEM FROM MOVING IN TRANSIT.  AWARENESS INTERVIEWS WILL TAKE PLACE WITH ALL PERSONS INVOLVED AND UP TO POSSIBLE DISCIPLINARY ACTION.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHWARD AT 25 MPH, GATX 63679, THE 45TH HEAD CAR IN TRAIN 135S DERAILED TO THE WEST SIDE OF THE TRACK,  ROLLED 450 DEGREE TO THE RIGHT AND PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE STUFFING BOX.  THE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED WITH A 24" WRENCH TO STOP THE SMALL FLOW OF FUEL FROM THE FITTING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERY AT STATION #1650 A CAR BACKED INTO FITTING CAND BROKE IT OFF & CAUSED SPILL. (DRIVER HAD ORANGE CONES SET OUT.)  SPILLED 40-45 GALLONS  OF UL GASOLINE.  WAS CONTAINED ON THE 1.2 FIRE DEPT ON THE SCENE.  USED SPILL HIT & PEAT SORB.  HAD 3 TRASH (PLASTIC) CANS WITH CONTAMINATES IN THEM.  THEY  WERE PICKED UP 7-20-2000,  BY ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY(AWAITING PAPERWORK PROCESSING) TO BE DISPOSED OFF) NO ONE WAS INJURED.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER, INSPECTION OF A SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLET OF FREIGHT WAS FOUND TO HAVE ONE BOX OF LEAKING PRODUCT.  LEAKING BOX WAS IN CENTER-TOP OF PALLET. OUTERMOST CONTAINER SHOWED NO SIGNS OF DAMAGE.  INSPECTION OF INNER PACKAGINGS WAS FOUND TO HAVE ONE PLASTIC BOTTLE OF PRODUCT WITH A CRUSHED BOTTOM-CORNER WITH A CUT IN THE BASIC PACKAGING CAUSING LEAKAGE.

column168: AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY, WE DISCOVERED A BOX CONTAINING PAILS OF ADHESIVE WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN ON TOP OF ANOTHER DRUM.  THE LED ON ONE PAIL HAD COME LOOSE CAUSING SOME SEEPAGE,  THE DRUM AND THE CASE ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION BY THE SHIPPER.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO OUR CUSTOMER, ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT RUBBED AGAINST THE PAIL CAUSING A DENT AROUND THE SEAL AND SOME MINOR SEE PAGE.  CUSTOMER ACCEPTED ENTIRE SHIPMENT.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: INITIATING EVENT:  HUMAN ERROR    ROOT CAUSE: OPERATOR INATTENTIVE TO SCHEDULE.

THE DRIVER FAILED TO DO A PROPER PRE-TRIP ON A  PRE-LOADED TRAILER AT THE ALTANTA TERMINAL BEFORE LEAVING THE TERMINAL.  ONE OF THE WASHOUT CAPS ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS NOT SECURE.  WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED THE SURGE FROM THE PRODUCT FORCED THE WASHOUT CAP OFF THE FITTING ON THE TRAILER.  THIS CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO COME OUT OF THE WASHOUT AREA ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.  FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE ROADWAY AND TWO GALLONS- STAYED ON THE TRAILER. McWHORTER TECHNOLOGIES SENT OUT A CLEAN-UP CREW TO CLEAN THE SPILL UP.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON THE IMPORTANCE OF DOING A PROPER PRE-TRIP ON A TANK TRAILER TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS.

WE WERE IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING WHEN THE PRODUCT PUMP ON THE TRACTOR STARTED TO LEAK AROUND THE PACKING GLAND.  THE DRIVER STOPPED THE OPERATION AND TIGHTENED THE PACKING ADJUSTMENT ON THE PUMP TO STOP THE LEAK.  ALL OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS CAUGHT IN A CONTAINER AND THEN DISPOSED OF BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL.  THE AMOUNT LEAKED AMOUNTED TO ONE HALF OF A GALLON.

column168: WHEN OUR DRIVER PICKED UP THE BOX FROM THE SHIPPER, IT WAS OK WHEN HE RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL HE DISCOVERED THAT THE BOX WAS LEAKING. WHEN HE LOOKED INSIDE OF THE BOX THERE WAS A PIECE OF A NAIL THAT HAD PUNCTURED THE INNER LINNER.  ABOUT A CUP FULL OF CHEMICAL HAD LEAKED OUT.  WE TURNED THE BOX ON ITS SIDE TO STOP IT FROM LEAKING. WE PUT BAKING SODA ON THE AREA WHERE IT HAD LEAKED TO NEUTRALIZE AND CONTAIN THE CHEMICAL.  THE NAIL WAS IN THE BOX AT THE TIME OF PICKUP.  THE OUTER BOX HAD NEVER BEEN OPENED.  APPARENTLY THE NAIL HAD GOT IN THE BOX FROM ONE OF THE HOLES FOR THE HANDLES.
ROOT CAUSE:  VALVE SEAT

column168: UNLOADING TRAILER AND DISCOVERED BOXES LEAKING OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE. A CERTIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE BOXES WERE RECOUPED INTO DOT APPROVED DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINERS, PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND ARE AWAITING SHIPPERS DISPOSITION.

WHILE MOVING OTHER FREIGHT, ONE DRUM WAS STRUCK AND PUNCTURED. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
ONE BOX WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED TO BE WET. THE BOX WAS PLACED INTO AN UNVENTED OVERPACK. THE GASES BUILT UP IN THE OVERPACK AND CAUSED THE LID TO POP OFF. A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO HANDLE THE OVERPACK AND SPILLAGE. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING EN ROUTE. A CERTIFIED RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. A LIQUID WAS DISCOVERED SEEPING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS THEN FORWARDED TO THE NEXT YELLOW FREIGHT FACILITY AWAITING SHIPPER DISPOSITION AND INSTRUCTIONS.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO PAILS WERE DISCOVERED CRUSHED, CAUSED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE PAILS WERE RECOUPED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINERS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: PASCHALL DRIVER PICKED UP LOAD IN DECATUR, AL AND STOPPED AT THE FLYING J. TRUCKSTOP IN KNOXVILLE, TN.  DRIVER CAME OUT OF TRUCKSTOP TO DISCOVER HE HAD PAINT DRIPPING THREW THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO THE UNDER CARRIGE OF HIS TRAILER.  AFTER THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE LOAD HE DISCOVERED HE HAD ONE DRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  EMI WAS CONTACTED AND THEY SENT OUT HEPCO TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE CLEAN UP CREW THAT THE 55 GALLON DRUM HAD A STRESS FRACTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BARREL WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  PER THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND EVERYTHING PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER TO BE ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION POINT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE PASCHALL DRIVER HAD ALREADY HAD 1 SPILL ON THIS LOAD IN KNOXVILLE, TN.  ON 07/23/00 SO HE WAS CHECKING IT FREQUENTLY TO MAKE SURE THERE WHERE NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.  HE STOPPED AT THE SHEETZ TRAVEL CENTER IN EDINBURGH, VA AND OPENED HIS LOAD TO CHECK FOR POSSIBLE PROBLEMS AND HE DISCOVERED ANOTHER 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT WAS LEAKING.  EMI WAS AGAIN CALLED AND THEY SENT OUT A&A ENVIRONMENTAL TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL CLEAN-UP.  ONCE AGAIN PER THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED UP AND OVERPACKED AND PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER TO BE ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO THE DESTINATION POINT WHERE THE LOAD, AS WELL AS, THE OVERPACKS WHERE ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.
HOSE STARTING LEAKING WHEN FIRST STARTED UNLOADING.  COMPANY PUT NETURALIZER ON AN CLEANED UP.

THE DELIVERY SPECIALIST WAS TRANSFERRING PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER BASE TANK. THE TRANSFER OPERATION TOOK PLACE INSIDE A 15 X 25 CEMENT CONTAINMENT BASIN. DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSFERRING THE  PRODUCT, THE DELIVERY SPECIALIST'S FOOT HIT THE INJECTION LINE GOING TO THE INJECTION PUMP. THE VIBRATION CAUSED WHEN THE LINE WAS BUMPED RESULTED IN A 3 OZ  SPILL WHEN THE PLASTIC PVC CONNECTION . CONNECTING THE INJECTION LINE TO THE PUMP BROKE. THE SPILL WAS WIPED UP BY THE DELIVERY SPECIALIST AND THE CONNECTION REPAIRED USING A STAINLESS STEEL CONNECTOR.

SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEES WERE STAGING DRUMS FOR A WASTE SHIPMENT GOING OUT FROM THE TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY. A FORKLIFT WAS MOVING THE DRUMS WHEN A 55 METAL GALLON DRUM FELL POPPING THE LID OFF. 33 GALLONS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT. THE WASTE GENERATED WAS CONTAINERIZED AND THE LID PLACED BACK ONTO THE DRUM SECURELY.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 350 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER , WHO PICKED UP THE DRUM, WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE PROCEDURES PRIOR TO SHIPMENT TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: TANK CAR LEAKING OUT MANWAY WHEN MOVED.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND MANWAY COVER GASKET DETERIORATED (SOFT), SLIDING OUT OF POSITION. TEMPORARY REPAIRS MADE TO SEAL MANWAY.  CAR DECONTAMINATED, WASHED & DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE. BNSF SWITCHMAN'S LEFT FOREARM CAME IN CONTACT WITH SPILLED PRODUCT ON CARS GRAB IRONS WHILE HE WAS RIDING ON CAR. BUT NO INJURY RECEIVED.  SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, YARD JOB SHOVED TRACK WITH POINT CAR (TANK CAR) COLLIDING WITH A LOADED COIL STEEL GONDOLA THAT WAS ROLLING FREELY ON LEAD TRACK THAT WAS SWITCHED BY ANOTHER YARD JOB. COLLISION RESULTED IN APPROX 6 INCH SLASH TO A-END TANK HEAD APPROX 2 FEET UP FROM BOTTOM HEAD SEAM, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM PUNCTURE.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED TO TANKER TRUCKS.  OVER 40% OF SPILLED PRODUCT ON GROUND WAS INITIALLY RECOVERED, WITH THE REMAINING SPILLED PRODUCT ON GROUND FLUSHED & NEUTRALIZED.  CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS FAILURE TO PROTECT SHOVING MOVEMENT DUE TO ABSENCE OF MAN ON OR AT THE LEADING END OF MOVEMENT.  BNSF HAS REEMPHASIZED THE IMPORTANCE OF PROTECTING MOVEMENTS IN A CURRENT BROADCAST OF SAFETY BRIEFING TOPICS ISSUED TO ALL EMPLOYEES ON JULY 18, 2000.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT WETNESS AT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC).  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) OPERATING ROD & PACKING GLAND NUT ONE TURN LOOSE. ALSO, ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE. RESPONDER TIGHTENED ALL LOOSE FITTINGS, INCLUDING BOC, WITH APPROPRIATE WRENCHES.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: CUT OF CARS STANDING ON YARD TRACK EMANATING ODOR.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND TWO CARS WITH SECUREMENT ISSUES.  THIS CAR HAD LOOSE FLANGE BOLTS (4) ON THE LOADING/UNLOADING VALVE.  ALSO, VAPOR LINE VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN & PLUG LOOSE. RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED BOLTS & PLUG, CLOSED VAPOR LINE VALE, ELIMINATING ODOR.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: CUT OF CARS STANDING ON YARD TRACK EMANATING ODOR.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND TWO CARS WITH SECUREMENT ISSUES.  THIS CAR HAD THE VAPOR LINE VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN & PLUG LOOSE.  RESPONDER CLOSED VALVE AND TIGHTENED PLUG WITH WRENCH, ELIMINATING ODOR.  CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

TANK CAR IN YARD VENTING AT SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV).  CONSIGNEE RESPONDERS FOUND THE FLANGE BOLTS AT THE SRV LOOSE & THESE TIGHTENED.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS NOT RUPTURED.  AFTER REPAIRS COMPLETED, VENTING CEASED.  CAR RELEASED TO CONSIGNEE & CONSIGNEE MADE THROUGH INSPECTION OF CAR PRIOR TO RELOADING.  SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT.

CONTAINER ARRIVED LEAKING UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE & WAS TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND ONE 5 GALLON METAL CAN THAT HAD BEEN PARTIALLY CRUSHED BY HEAVIER LADING PLACED ATOP IT.  OTHER NON-HAZ LADING INCURRED SAME FATE. RESPONDERS REMEDIATED SPILLED PRODUCTS & ADJUSTED LOAD.

CAR REPORTED WITH SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT NEAR MANWAY COVER.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS MISSING AND VOID WAS PLUGGED TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM SPLASHING OUT.  CAR RELEASED TO CONSIGNEE. BOTH CONSIGNEE & SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THIS DEFECT.  CAR TO BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS PRIOR TO RELOADING.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE CHECKING BAD ORDER CARS ON ADJACENT TRACK, ODOR NOTICED EMANATING FROM STANDING CUT OF SIX CARS, BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND TWO CARS WITH LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WHICH WERE TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING ODOR. LOOSE CAP, CONTENTS LEAKED.  SPILL CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO DMP.  TOTAL SCRAP.

RESPONDED TO DR #31 WITH SPILL CART, IDENTIFIED PACKAGE AS HAZARDOUS, DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEETS, FOR KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD WERE USED.  ABSORBED THE SPILL AND PLACED THE WASTE IN A GREEN PLASTIC BAG FOR DISPOSAL VIA DMP.
WORE PROPER PPE.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE TO CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  THEN THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.

column168: RESPOND TO DOOR #7 IN FULL PPE USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND CORROSIVE GUIDE PAGES TO CLEAN THE SPILL.  I THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

TO AVOID THE POSSIBILITY OF HAVING THE SAFETY VENT OPEN WHILE TRAVELING ON THE ROAD, THEY PULLED INTO A TRUCK STOP IN MONTGOMERY, AL. USF HOLLAND TRAILER 205665 ARRIVED AT OUR TERMINAL IN WAUSAU, WI AND THE DOCKMAN BROUGHT TO OUR INBOUND SUPV ATTENTION THAT THE TOTE HAD SPLASHED SOME OF IT'S CONTENT IN THE TRAILER...ON ITSELF AND OTHER NEARBY SHIPMENTS.  UPON EXAMINING THE 300 GAL TOTE, WE SAW THAT THE CHEMICAL INSIDE HAD SPLASHED OUT OF THE TOP.  UPON FURTHER VIEW OF THE TOP OF THE TOTE, WE COULD SEE THAT A AIR-VENT PLUG WAS OFF AND LAYING ON TOP OF THE TOTE.  THE OPEN HOLE WHERE THE PLUG SHOULD HAVE BEEN, WHICH WAS APPROX 1.5" IN DIAMETER, IS WHERE THE CHEMICAL HAD SPLASHED OUT OF.  WE THEN, IMMEDIATELY CALLED OUR SAFETY DEPT IN HOLLAND, MI AND PER THEIR INSTRUCTION, DETERMINED THAT A HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL CLEANUP WOULD BE NECESSARY.  AFTER GETTING THE SHIPPER INVOLVED, THEY AGREED.
UPON UNLOADING ONE DRUM FOUND WITH FORK HOLE.  PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM.
DRIVER HIT WITH FORK BLADE - CHECKER IMMEDIATELY LAYED ON SIDE - ABOUT 1 CUP LOST.  PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM.  SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED WITH FLOOR-DRI.
1 GALLON CONTAINER OF TURPENTINE SUBSTITUTE HAD FALLEN OVER IN TRL ABOUT 1/2 GALLON EVAPORATED.  THE DAMAGED CAN WAS RECOVERED AND THERE WAS NO DEBRIS FOR DISPOSAL.

OUR UNIT WAS PREPARING TO UNLOAD OUR TRAILER IN THE RODIA PLANT IN LULING LA.  AFTER HOOKING THE UNLOADING HOSES UP,  OUR DRIVER ENGAGED HIS TRACTOR PRODUCT PUMP AND APPROX 300 LBS OF PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE PRODUCT PUMP BLEEDER VALVE SPILLING ONTO THE PLANT UNLOADING RACK FLOOR WHICH IS A CONTAINED AREA.  INVESTATION REVEALED THAT THE PRODUCT PUMP BLEEDR VALVE WELD WAS BROKEN WHERE IT WAS WELDED TO THE DISCHARGE PIPE.  THE PLANT CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT SPILL AND WILL INVOICE E.T.C.  FOR THE CLEANUP

THE LOADER WAS IN THE ACT OF TRANSFERRING SULFURIC ACID WHEN THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK PULLED AWAY WITH THE HOSES STILL ATTACHED, TRANSFERRING PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER THOUGHT THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE AND SIMPLY PULLED OUT WITH THE HOSE UNDER PRESSURE ALLOWING THE SPILL OF 1282 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID.  COMPRESSED IS USED FOR THIS TYPE OF TRANSFER.

WHEN THIS PIECE ARRIVED IN BREAK DOWN, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM WHICH WAS LEAKING FLUID ONTO THE PALLET UPON WHICH IT WAS SITTING.  SOME OF THE LIQUID HAD SPILLED ON THE MAIN DECK OF THE IN BOUND N/C (N612GC) .  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND FAA APPROVED CLEANING SOLUTION THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS HELD FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: GATX 99871 WAS NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED OVER SPILL CONTAINMENT AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP STOPPING THE RELEASE.

GATX 48321 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, CHLOREP TEAM FROM OLIN CHEMICAL IN NIAGRA, NY, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  THE BOLTS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: MINERAL SPIRITS REGULAR WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM TANK CAR UTLX 202786 TO A BULK TANK.  THE BULK TANK RAN OVER WHEN THE CAR FINISHED THE TRANSFER.  OPERATOR RECORDED BEGINNING READING ON TANK GAUGE AND CALCULATED THE AVAILABLE ROOM IN THE TANK.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT THERE WAS ROOM IN THE TANK FOR THE MATERIAL IN THE CAR.  THE TANK IS EQUIPPED WITH A HIGH LEVEL ALARM.  THE CAR WAS BEING UNLOADED VIA NITROGEN.  WHEN THE PRODUCT FINISHED TRANSFERRING AND THE NITROGEN GAS RUSHED THROUGH THE PRODUCT LINE TO THE TANK ABOUT 350 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS DISPLACED AND OVERFLOWED THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM DID NOT SOUND.  ALL BUT ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT WITHIN THE TANK FARM.  (THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY WAS NOT REACHED).  THE SPILLED MINERAL SPIRITS WAS PUMPED UP INTO TOTES. THIS WAS THE FIRST TIME THE TANK WAS FILLED.  CONTRACTOR CAME IN 7 - 21 - 00 AND REPAIRED THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM.  CONTRACTOR RE-CALIBRATED THE LEVEL INDICATOR ON 7 - 21 - 00 ALSO.

A TRAILER WAS WAITING TO BE ACCEPTED INTO A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 1 - 2 GALLONS OF A LIQUID HAD SPILLED ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, THERE WAS ANOTHER 13 GALLONS OF LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS A SOLUTION CONTAINING LEAD AND CAME FROM A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WHICH DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE PARKING LOT WITH ABSORBENT AND THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS BEING LOADED INTO A TRAILER AT TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY.  THEY WERE USING A FORKLIFT WITH A DRUM GRABBER TO MOVE THE DRUMS.  WHILE PICKING UP THE WASTE, THE GRABBER MADE A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM AND HALF A GALLON SPILLED OUT ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.

THE DRUMS WERE BEING PALLETIZED WHEN A NAIL FROM THE PALLET PIERCED THOUGH THE BOTTOM OF A 5 GALLON POLY DRUM CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC AND SULFURIC ACID. 1 GALLON OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE SPILLED ACID WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND THE 5 GALLON DRUM WAS OVERPACKED.
OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.

column168: DRIVER HIT HOLE IN ROAD WHILE MAKING A LEFT TURN.  SOME SKIDS TIPED OVER TO THE RIGHT CAUSING PAILS TO BE ON THEIR SIDE.  WHEN DISCOVERED AT 1830 WE CALLED WCEC AND HAD THEM COME OUT.  WCEC STARTED TO CLEAN UP WHAT HAD SPILLED AND THEY NOTICED THAT SOME OF THE PAILS HAD BEEN LEAKING PREVIOUS TO VITRAN PICKING THEM UP.  THE PAILS WERE LEAKING OUT OF THE SPOUTS ON TOP AND AROUND THE LID OF THE PAIL.  WE TALKED TO DRIVER ABOUT SECURING HIS FREIGHT WHEN PICKING UP .  WE ALSO WENT OVER MAKING SURE HE INSPECTS WHAT HE PICKS UP AND MAKING SURE THAT THE INFO ON THE BILL MATCHES WHATS ON THE FREIGHT.

DRUM OVERPACKED & LOAD TRANSFERED TO ANOTHER TRAILER. TRAILER WITH SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED.

column168: BNSF CARMAN REPORTED CAR DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OUTLET WHILE CAR STANDING ON YARD TRACKS. BNSF RESPONDER FOUND THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) TOOK TWO FULL TURNS TO FULLY CLOSE VALVE. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHT. SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED. CORRECTIONS MADE WITHIN TEN MINUTES AFTER RESPONDERS ARRIVAL. AFTERWARDS CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT.

DRIVER PICKED UP LOADED SHIPPER TRAILER AT MILFORD, VA ( JONES CHEMICAL INC). HE STARTED TOWARD HIS DESTINATION, CHARLOTTE NC AND HAD TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 50 MILES WHEN A DRIVER PASSED HIM AND INDICATED A PROBLEM. OUR DRIVER PULLED INTO THE REST AREA ON I 85 AT THE 55 MILE MAKER TO CHECK HIS LOAD. THERE WAS A CYLINDER OF CHLORINE LEAKING. JONES CHEMICAL REPORTED TO THE RELEASE TO HANDLE THE COORDINATION OF THE CLEAN UP. OUR DRIVER GOT A WIFF OF CHLORINE AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED. HE WAS RELEASED AND WENT BACK TO THE UNIT. NATIONAL RESPONSE NUMBER 536141.

column168: LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE PLUG NOT TOOL TIGHT, GATX 45729, JULY 19,2000 DETROIT DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, JULY 19, 2000, AT LINCOLN YARD IN MELVINDALE, MICHIGAN, FRA INSPECTOR GARY THOMPSON NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM TANK CAR GATX 45729, CONTAINING NITRATES, INORGANIC, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, N.O.S. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 HOURS, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM SAVAGE FLEXI FLO ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT. SAVAGE SECURED THE TANK CAR BY TIGHTENING THE LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE PLUG.

column168: THE RAILROAD SWITCHING CREW CAME INTO OUR FACILITY TO SWITCH OUT AN EMPTY RAILCAR ON OUR SIDING. RAILCAR NO. PROX 14695 WAS SETTING IN FRONT OF AN EMPTY RAILCAR THAT WAS TO BE SWITCHED OUT. DURING THE MOVEMENT OF THE SULFURIC ACID RAILCAR NO. PROX 14695, THE UNLOADING PIPING SEPARATED DUE TO STRIPPED OUT THREADS ON A PIPING REDUCER. THE RAIL-CAR STILL HAD PRESSURE ON IT. IN THE FUTURE, RAILCAR PRESSURE WILL BE BLED OFF IMMEDIATELY AFTER TRANSFER INTO STORAGE AND UNLOAD PIPING WILL BE REMOVED FROM RAILCARS BEFORE RAILCARS WILL BE ALLOWED TO BE MOVED.

column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DRIVER SPOTTED CARGO TANK NEXT TO RAIL CAR TO BE LOADED.  DRIVER WAS IN CAB AND MANAGER WALKED TO THE BACK OF AREA WERE CARGO TANK WAS BEING LOADED FROM RAIL CAR AND WAVED TO THE DRIVER FROM REAR TO MOVE FORWARD.  DRIVER STARTED TO MOVE FORWARD AND CHECK HIS RIGHT MIRROR AND SAW THE HOSE PULL AWAY FROM THE RAIL CAR.  ALL VALVES WERE SHUT DOWN.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES.

DRIER FAILED TO USE PROPER PROCEDURE WHILE DISCONNECTING HOSES AFTER UNLOADING.  WHILE DISCONNECTING HOSES, PRODUCT STILL IN THE HOSE WAS SPILLED.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS.  THE SHERMAN FIRE DEPART RESPONDED AND HOSED DOWN THE DIESEL.  SOME OF THE DIESEL AND WATER WASHED INTO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN.  GARNER ENVIR. WAS CALLED TO PERFORM CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP OF PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FROM EMPLOYMENT DUE TO THIS OCCURRENCE.

THE CENEX HARVEST STATES FUEL TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US HWY 14 APPROACHING BROWNS CHURCH RD.  A ROAD GRADER HAD JUST TURNED EAST ON US HWY 14 FROM BROWNS CHURCH RD WHEN A TRUCK THAT WAS FOLLOWING THE GRADED STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION AND PROCEEDED ACROSS NOT SEEING THE CENEX HARVEST STATES FUEL TRUCK.  THE FUEL TRUCK HIT THE BRAKES APPROXIMATELY 90 FT FROM THE INTERSECTION, BUT HIT THE OTHER TRUCK BROADSIDE AT APPROXIMATELY THE REAR AXLE.  THE CENEX HARVEST STATES FUEL TRUCK SUSTAINED ENOUGH DAMAGE TO A CAUSE RELEASE IN ITS CARGO TANK.

CARRIER UNLOADED MATERIAL INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK AS DIRECTED. WHEN FINISHED UNLOADING DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DISCONNECT OUR HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S INLET LINE.  CUSTOMER'S IN-LINE CHECK VALVE APPARENTLY FAILED TO OPERATE AND PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW BACK OUT OF THE CUSTOMER'S INLET LINE.  CAPPING THE OUTLET WAS UNSUCCESSFUL DUE TO THE FORCE OF THE RELEASING PRODUCT.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS THEN FLOWING INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA SURROUNDING THE STORAGE TANK. THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS DAMAGED AND/OR "UNPLUGGED" AND PRODUCT THEN BEGAN FLOWING DOWN A HILL APPROXIMATELY 200 FT AND INTO A STORM DRAIN.  THE CUSTOMER NOTIFIED AUTHORITIES.  ONCE THE ATLANTA FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED, THE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASED PRODUCT BY DAMMING THE FLOW OF LIQUID.  THEY ALSO BEGIN TO FLUSH THE RELEASED PRODUCT WITH WATER.  THE RECEIVING CUSTOMER CALLED IN A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR FOR CLEAN UP OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT. THE EPA AND CITY OFFICIALS MONITORED THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING CONDINSATE GAS FROM TRAILER INTO TANK FACILITY WHEN VAPOR FROM THE CONDINSATE IGNITED.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER COMPLETELY BURNED, ALONG WITH THE 190 BARRELS OF CONDINSATE.  NO DAMAGE WAS DONE TO THE STORAGE TANKS, A SMALL OFFICE BUILDING WAS DAMAGED IN THE FIRE.  PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING SAFETY PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN RE-EMPHASIZED TO ALL DRIVERS.  THE DRIVER WAS SEVERELY BURNED AND DIED FROM HIS INJURIES ON AUGUST 6, 2000, THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON JULY 18, 2000.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT HIS FACILITY WHEN HE DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE GASOLINE HAD A LID WITH A DEFECTIVE GASKET AND HAD MATERIAL LEAKING OUT OF THE TOP.  WHILE REPLACING THE LID, ADDITIONAL MATERIAL SPILLED.  A TOTAL OF ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE DOCK AREA WHICH WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KY FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. column168: A TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED AT TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY WHEN AN EMPLOYEE PUNCTURED A 16 GALLON DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT.  FIFTEEN GALLONS OF WASTE PAINT SPILLED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  IT WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AD CONTAINERIZED INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 150 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED,ALONG WITH ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 E 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE FORKLIFT DIVER WAS COUNSELED PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT ALONG WITH THE CYLINDER WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED,  55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 55 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE  CEMENT UNDER THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: FORMIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 85% ACID BY MASS
column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE, 400 GALLON METAL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAULTY VALVE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT RAGS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY  DRUM, ONE, FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE,FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE VALVE ON THE LEAKING TOTE WAS SECURED. THE TOTE WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, THREE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE TABLESPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DO TO LOOSE BREATHER CAPS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE PPE WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A SECOND THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BREATHER CAPS WERE TIGHTENED ON THE THREE LEAKING DRUMS AND THEY WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING FROM A CITY TRUCK, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TEN OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO PACKAGING FAILURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP BY USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP  MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE ABSORBENTS AND FREE PRODUCTS WERE PLACED INTO A SECOND FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE BETWEEN ORIGIN AND DESTINATION THE DRIVER NOTICED A FEW DROPS OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, A LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AFTER PULLING THE PALLET OF FREIGHT OUT OF THE TRAILER, THE CONWAY EMPLOYEE NOTICED TWO BAGS OF THE SHIPMENT LEAKING.  THE FREIGHT HAD BEEN JAMMED AGAINST ANOTHER PALLET AND CAUSED THE TWO BAGS TO TEAR. I THEN INSTRUCTED THE CONWAY EMPLOYEE TO PLACE INTO AN EMPTY TRAILER AND CLOSE THE DOOR.  WE PUT A LOCK ON THE TRAILER AND KEPT IT ISOLATED AWAY FROM OUR WORK AREA.  I THEN NOTIFIED OUR REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND CHEM_TEL OF THE INCIDENT.  I WAS INSTRUCTED TO CLEAN SPILL DUE TO THE FACT THAT IS WAS A SMALL AMOUNT AND THE SUBSTANCE WAS GRANULES.  I PERFORMED THIS DUTY AND THE TWO DAMAGE BAGS AND SMALL  AMOUNT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS PUT INSIDE AN OVERPACK DRUM.  AN INCIDENT REPORT WAS FILLED OUT FOR CONWAY.  MY RECOMMENDATIONS TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS OF THIS NATURE IS TO USE DUNNAGE AROUND BAGS.

A DRUM WAS AT TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY AND WAS BEING LOADED INTO A TRAILER HEADING FOR THE DRUMS FINAL DESTINATION. THE PALLET BENEATH THE 55 GALLON DRUM BROKE AND IT FELL OFF SPILLING 35 GALLONS OF ACETONE AND ACETIC ACID SOLUTION ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE 55 GALLON DRUM.THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 300 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 5756 ALBA STREET IN LOS ANGELES, CA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DIVER HANDLING THE WASTE WAS COUNSELED  PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURES BEFORE MOVING MATERIAL TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THE DRIVER WAS IN TRANSIT FROM A CUSTOMER SITE TO HIS FACILITY WHEN HE WAS ALERTED BY ANOTHER MOTORIST THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. HE PULLED OVER ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY AND INSPECTED THE LOAD. HE DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK SPILLING 12 GALLONS OF WASTE PAINT. THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER WITH 2 GALLONS LEAKING ON THE SHOULDER. THE SPILL INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ON HE SHOULDER WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND WASTE CONTAINERIZED. THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 150 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1340 WEST LINCOLN STREET IN PHOENIX, AZ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION BEFORE ACCEPTING A LOAD FOR TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE TRUCK AT HIS FACILITY WHEN HE DISCOVERED A 16 GALLON METAL DRUM HAD A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM SEAM. A TOTAL OF 1 GALLON OF PETROLEUM DISTILLATES SPILLED  INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND ONE QUART SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT. column168: THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED AT APPROXIMATELY 8:15 A.M. ON JULY 19, 2000 , IN THE HERITAGE TRANSPORT WEST PARKING LOT WHERE DRUM TRAILERS ARE STAGED. A DRIVER PICKING UP AN EMPTY TRAILER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM A PLACARDED DRUM VAN, DRUM VANS ARE STAGED AT HERITAGE TRANSPORT'S PHYSICAL LOCATION AT1626 RESEARCH WAY, INDIANAPOLIS. THIS IS 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY FOR HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TSDF. THE MATERIAL WAS WASTEWATER TREATMENT SLUDGE CONTAINING CHROMIC ACID, CADMIUM, AND LEAD.THE WASTE CODES WERE D002,D006,D007,AND D008. THE RQ'S FOR ALL CODES IS 10LBS. EXCEPT FOR D002 WHICH IS 100LBS. AN ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER WHICH COVERED APPROXIMATELY 10,000 FT2. THE DRUMS CONTAINING THE CHROMIC ACID HAD MOST LIKELY BEGUN LEAKING IN THE NIGHT. SINCE IT HAD ALSO RAINED HEAVILY THAT EVENING.THE RELEASED MATERIAL ENTERED THE PARKING LOT STORM DRAIN SYSTEM AND HAD MIGRATED TO AN ON-SITE STORMWATER RETENTION POND. NO INJURIES OCCURRED FROM THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE. THE MATERIAL RELEASED INTO THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM WAS FLUSHED AND VACUUM PUMPED UNTIL THE DETECTION LEVELS OF CHROMIC ACID WERE LESS THAN 0.5 PPM. THE STORMWATER POND WAS DECONNED WITH CHROMIC ACID DETECTION AT LESS THAN 0.1 PPM. THE CLEANUP EFFORTS BEGAN FROM THE TIME OF DISCOVERY OF THE LEAKING DRUMS UNTIL 4:30 A.M. THE NEXT DAY TO ASSURE COMPLETE DECONTAMINATION OF THE STORMWATER DRAIN SYSYTEM, PARKING LOT, AND POND. THE MATERIAL RELEASED ON THE PARKING LOT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE, POWER WASHED AND VACUUMED INTO A DOT APPROVED VACUUM TRUCK. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN TAKEN TO HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TSDF AT 7901 W. MORRIS STREET FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. ALL ORIGINAL CHROMIC ACID SLUDGE DRUMS FROM THE VAN WERE OVER PACKED INTO 95 GALLON PGI RATED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE CHROMIC ACID SLUDGE HAD BEEN ORIGINALLY PLACED INTO STEEL DRUMS BY THE GENERATOR, GUARDIAN AUTOMOTIVE. APPROXIMATELY 8000 GALLONS OF RINSE WATER HAD BEEN RECOVERED FROM THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM AND POND INLET AREA. SEVERAL SAMPLES OF THE POND HAD BEEN TAKEN INCLUDING WHERE THE STORMWATER SYSTEM DRAINS INTO THE POND AND OPPOSITE SHORELINES. ALTHOUGH DOT DOES ALLOW THE USE OF STEEL DRUMS FOR CHROMIC ACID, WE ARE INFORMING OUR CUSTOMERS THAT STEEL DRUMS ARE NOT ACCEPTABLE FOR CONTAINMENT OF CHROMIC ACID.

column168: ON JULY 19, 2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 18:30:00 HOURS,  A RAILROAD TANK CAR,  GATX 23356, LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS'S KANSAS CITY,  MISSOURI RAIL YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO AN INACTIVE, TRACK #13, TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE SPILLAGE.  THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY (SHIPPER)  WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE PROVIDING FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS AND DECONTAMINATION.

A DRIVER WAS ON HIS WAY TO THE FACILITY WHEN HE DISCOVERED THAT HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING. ON INSPECTION OF THE LOAD, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 40 GALLONS OF OIL CONTAMINATED WITH POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYLS HAD LEAKED OUT OF A 55 GALLON DRUM INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND THE LEAKING DRUM OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 350 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 500 BATTLEGROUND ROAD IN LA PORTE, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURES TOE ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED. HE WAS MOVING A 30 GALLON POLY DRUM ONTO HIS LIFT GATE WHEN HE LOST CONTROL OF THE DRUM AND IT FELL ONTO THE CONCRETE PARKING AREA. ONE OF THE BUNGS POPPED OFF AND 10 GALLONS OF PHOTO FIXER SOLUTION WITH SILVER SPILLED OUT. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTANERIZED. THE BUNG WAS PLACED BACK ONTO THE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE STREET, IN CANTON, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM HANDLING AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER SECURED 55 GALLON DRUM TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AS THE DRUM WAS HIS NEXT DELIVERY AT HIS NEXT STOP. AS HE PULLED OUT ONTO THE PUBLIC STREET TOWARDS HIS NEXT STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID AND FUMES COMING FROM THE LEFT REAR OF HIS TRAILER. HE STOPPED IN THE STREET AND CALLED FOR HELP. ONCE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ARRIVED THE DRUM WAS STILL SECURED BY TWO LOAD LOCKS. THE DRUM BOTTOM HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE ACID TO LEAK OUT. HAVING DRUM EXAMINED TO VERIFY REASON FOR FAILURE AND WORKING WITH SHIPPER ONCE WE HAVE RESULTS OF REASON FOR FAILURE.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: CARRIER WAS TRANSPORTING A PALLET CONTAINING FOUR DRUMS OF H/M.  THE SHIPPER HAD SHRINK WRAPPED THE DRUMS TOGETHER BUT NOT TO THE PALLET. WHEN THE VEHICLE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE, ONE DRUM HAD SHIFTED OFF THE PALLET THAT WAS ON AND HAD STRUCK A PROTRUDING NAIL. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS HAD SPILLED ON TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND WAS REACTING WITH THE TRAILERS ALUMINUM FLOOR.  IT HAD ALREADY ATTACKED AN AREA EIGHT INCHES IN DIAMETER ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CONSIGNEE'S STAFF ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST HAD TAKEN MEASURES TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE WITH OIL DRY AND TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO A PLASTIC SALVAGE DRUM.  THE CARRIER RETAINED AND SENT A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO THE SPILL SITE.  IN THE MEANTIME, THE CONSIGNEE'S SPECIALIST CALLED TO REPORT THAT EATEN A HOLE COMPLETELY THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE SAID THAT THE PRODUCT HAD COMPLETELY REACTED WITH THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THERE WAS A HOLE ALL THE WAY THROUGH THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS ALSO PRODUCT ON THE TIRES AND THE ALUMINUM WHEEL WELL.  THE HEAT FROM THE REACTION ON THE WHEEL CAUSED SOME OF THE TIRES TO MELT.  THE SPECIALIST NOTIFIED THE NORTH CAROLINA EMERGENCY RESPONSE HOTLINE.  THE WAKE COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM DISPATCHED A REPRESENTATIVE.  BY THE TIME THAT THE REPRESENTATIVE ARRIVED THERE WAS A 4' X 4' STAIN ON THE GROUND DIRECTLY UNDER THE TRAILER AND A TRAIL LEADING TOWARD THEIR PARKING LOT.  A SUPERVISOR FROM THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED.  AS THE DAY WAS A SATURDAY THERE WERE NO OTHER EMPLOYEES AVAILABLE TO RESPOND.  THE SUPERVISOR BEGAN THE CLEANUP USING LIME TO NEUTRALIZE THE PRODUCT. ANY MATERIAL THAT HE COULD RECOVER WAS PUT INTO PLASTIC DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  LIME WAS PLACED ON ALL CONTAMINATED SURFACES AND THEN SWEPT UP.  THE CONSIGNEE HAD AND PROVIDED THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WITH AN MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.  WHEN NOTIFIED BY THE CARRIER VIA CHEM TREC, THE SHIPPER CALLED BACK TO OFFER ASSISTANCE AND TO ASK THAT THE DAMAGED DRUM BE OVERPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THEM FOR INSPECTION. THE CONTRACTOR DID SO AND PLACED THE OVERPACK ON THE TRAILER.  IT WAS TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S  FACILITY FOR DELIVERY BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE COUNTY REPRESENTATIVE REPORTED THAT HE WAS PLEASED WITH THE WAY THE CLEANUP WAS GOING AND HE WOULD BE IN TOUCH WITH THE CARRIER TO FOLLOW UP.  FOUR HOURS AFTER ONSET OF THE INCIDENT, THE VEHICLE AND DRIVER WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGED TIRES WERE REPLACED OR REPAIRED AT A LOCAL TRUCK STOP. TWO TIRES WERE SHOWING SIGNS OF MELTING BUT WERE SAFE FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER' FACILITY.  THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY AND PLACED OUT OF SERVICE FOR REPAIRS.  FIVE AND ONE HALF HOURS AFTER HOURS AFTER ONSET THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE SITE OCCUPANT AND TO THE COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL REPRESENTATIVE.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND THE MELTED TIRES WERE ULTIMATELY SENT TO THE CARRIER'S CORPORATE HEADQUARTERS FOR INSPECTION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THIS DRUM ARRIVED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY SHOWING LEAKAGE FROM A CRACK IN ITS BOTTOM HEAD.  CARRIER'S DOCK PERSONNEL WIPED UP THE SPILLAGE, PUT THE DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SET IT ASIDE FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

DURING STRIPPING OF INBOUND TRAILER FROM THE SHIPPER, ONE "MICRO PORTAFEED" WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM ITS VALVE.  IT WAS HELD OFF BY THE CARRIER AT ITS FACILITY.  AT THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER IT WAS PUT INTO  A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING LOCATION.

AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND ENCOUNTERED AN OVERPOWERING ODOR.  THERE SHIPMENT BEING DELIVERED WAS AN I B C OF A GLUTERALDEHYDE PRODUCT SITUATED AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER COULD SEE SPILLAGE DOWN THE SIDES OF THE I B C AND SOME MATERIAL IN THE ALUMINUM GROOVES OF THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE ODOR WAS SO STRONG THAT HE COULD NOT ENTER THE TRAILER.  UPON NOTIFICATION, THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED HIM TO STAY CLEAR OF IT.  HAZMAT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC AND REQUESTED AN MSDS.  CARRIER ALSO RETAINED A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO DECONTAMINATE THE TOTE AND THE TRAILER.  DRIVER CALLED BACK; THERE IS SOME MATERIAL LEAKING OUT ONTO THE GROUND FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON LOCATION WITH ONE SUPERVISOR AND ONE TECHNICIAN.  THEIR INSTRUCTIONS WERE REVISED TO INCLUDE AND SITE DECONTAMINATION NEEDED.  THEY PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILLAGE AND CONTAINED IT.  A SECOND UNIT OF THE CARRIER ARRIVED ON LOCATION TO RECEIVE OTHER SHIPMENTS THAT WERE ON THE SPILL TRAILER.  THE CONSIGNEE OF THE FAILED I B C WOULD NOT ALLOW THEM TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AT THEIR LOCATION.  THEY ALSO WOULDN'T LET IT LEAVE UNTIL IT WAS STABILIZED.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPERVISOR REPORTED THAT HAD IT STABILIZED.  IT WAS FIRST THOUGHT THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM A LOOSE FILL CAP.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION DISCLOSED A HOLE IN THE TOP RADIUS AREA OF THE I B C.  THE CAUSE OF THE HOLE WAS UNKNOWN.  THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPERVISOR PROPOSED MOVING THE ENTIRE OPERATION TO THEIR TO THEIR NEARBY FACILITY.  THERE IS ADEQUATE SPACE AT THAT LOCATION TO BACK THE TWO TRAILERS UP TO EACH OTHER AND TRANSFER THE UNAFFECTED FREIGHT.  WHEN ALL OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED, THE I B C'S ALONG WITH THE BALANCE OF THE FREIGHT WERE TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY PENDING INSPECTION AND DISPOSITION.  CARRIER NOTES A VIRTUALLY IDENTICAL INCIDENT OCCURRED ON 5/16/2000.  THE SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE AND TYPE OF PACKAGING AND NATURE OF THE FAILURE WERE THE SAME IN BOTH CASES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: A SHIPMENT OF REPORTEDLY EMPTY PORTABLE TANKS WAS PICKED UP BY THE CARRIER FOR RETURN TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED BEHIND SEVERAL PALLETS OF ANOTHER SHIPMENT.  THE FIRST FOUR TANKS WERE DOUBLE STACKED.  AS THERE IS NO LOADING DOCK AT THE PICK UP POINT, AND SINCE IT WAS RAINING, THE DRIVER REMAINED IN HIS CAB DURING TH LOADING PROCESS.  WHEN THE LOADING WAS COMPLETED, THE DRIVER FOUND THAT HE COULD NOT MAKE ACCESS TO THE TANKS IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER, SO HE DEPARTED ENROUTE TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. HE EXPECTED THAT THE TANKS WOULD BE SAFE FOR TRANSIT DUE TO THEIR NESTING PROVISIONS.  AT THE  CARRIER'S FACILITY A DOCK PERSON OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND DISCOVERED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR COMING FROM ONE OF TWO TANKS THAT HAD TOPPLED OVER ENROUTE.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT TANK STILL CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL PRODUCT.  SOME PRODUCT ESCAPED TO THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE TRAILER.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE MITIGATION OF THE SITUATION.  MINIMAL MIGRATION OF THE MATERIAL HAD TAKEN PLACE WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED.  THEY WERE ABLE TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND.  THEN, IN COORDINATION WITH THE CARRIER'S DOCK PERSONNEL, THEY UNLOADED THE FREIGHT, NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLAGE AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ONCE DONE, THE CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED THE SPILL AREA ON THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE TRAILER. TWO DRUMS OF WASTE WERE GENERATED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER HAD PARKED FOR THE NIGHT IN A REMOTE ROADSIDE REST AREA. WHEN HE AWOKE THE NEXT MORNING HE FOUND AN UNKNOWN LIQUID RUNNING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER CALLED 911 VIA CELLULAR TELEPHONE. VARIOUS LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE ENTITIES RESPONDED.  AN OFFICIAL OF THE BOWIE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY CONTACTED THE CARRIER. THE CARRIER RETAINED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SITE TO LOCATE AND SECURE THE LEAKING PACKAGE(S), AND TO CONDUCT ANY NEEDED SITE REMEDIATION.  AS THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS THEN UNKNOWN, THE CONTRACTOR INITIALLY WORKED IN LEVEL "A" PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  AS THE TEMPERATURE WAS 102 DEGREES THEY WERE LIMITED TO WORKING IN 15 MINUTE INCREMENTS.  THE CONTRACTOR PLACED ABSORBENT PADS ON TO THE GROUND TO SOAK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT, AND ALSO USED BUCKETS TO CATCH PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM TRAILER UPON OPENING DOOR. SOME PRODUCT LEAKED INTO A DITCH ALONG THE REST STOP PAVEMENT. THERE WAS A POOL OF PRODUCT ABOUT A FOOT WIDE THAT NEEDED TO BE CLEANED UP IN THAT AREA.  THE PRODUCT THAT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WAS ABOUT 3/4 OF THE WAY UP IN THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS IN A PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKING FROM A HOLE THAT RESULTED FROM A SHIFT OF THE FREIGHT TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS AN APPROXIMATE LOSS  OF 40 GALLONS OF THIS PRODUCT.  SEVERAL OTHER DRUMS WERE LYING ON THEIR SIDES.  THE DRUMS WERE ON PALLETS AND POORLY SHRINK WRAPPED.  THERE WAS NOTHING SECURING THEM TO THE PALLETS, NOR ANYTHING USED TO BRACE THE DRUMS FROM SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT HAS BEEN DETERMINED TO BE A LOAD SHIFT.  THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LOADED BY THE SHIPPER ONTO THE INVOLVED TRAILER AT THEIR FACILITY IN CINCINNATI, OHIO.  PLASTIC DRUMS WERE SHIPPED ON PALLETS, SHRINK WRAPPED TO EACH OTHER BUT NOT TO THE PALLETS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS A "HEAD LOAD"  AND WAS NOT FURTHER HANDLED BY THE CARRIER.  THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 70 DRUMS ON 18 PALLETS.  SEVENTEEN PALLETS EACH HELD FOUR DRUMS.  THE EIGHTEENTH PALLET HAD TWO DRUMS AND A FIVE GALLON PAIL ON IT.  IT WAS LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THIS CREATED A VOID SPACE.  THE SHIPPER LOADED THE PALLETS OF DRUMS BEHIND IT WITH NO OTHER SECUREMENT PROVIDED.  THE OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE LOADED AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, BEHIND THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT.  DURING TRANSIT, THE SHRINK WRAP ON AT LEAST ONE OF THE ORIGINAL PALLETS FAILED, LEAVING ITS DRUMS ADRIFT.  SOME OF THE DRUMS MIGRATED INTO THE VOID SPACE AND TUMBLED OVER.  ONE DRUM STRUCK A PALLET AND BROKE OPEN, ALLOWING ITS CONTENTS TO ESCAPE INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD BY THE CONTRACTOR PENDING SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: DRIVER WAS AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP MAKING A DELIVERY WHEN HE FOUND THAT A PAIL OF H/M HAD LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE PAIL AND ANOTHER OF NON-REGULATED MATERIAL WERE LOADED ON THE LEFT SIDE, TAIL END OF THE TRAILER.  STRAPS WERE PLACED THROUGH THE HANDLES AND THE PAILS WERE SURROUNDED BY 2X2'S AND CHOCKED IN.  SEVERAL NAILS THAT SECURED THE CHOCKS WERE NOT HAMMERED IN ALL THE WAY.  DURING TRANSIT THE PAILS BOUNCED ONTO THE NAIL HEADS CAUSING THEM TO PUNCTURE AND TO LEAK.  THE COMPANY AT THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT HAS ITS OWN IN-HOUSE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WHO ASSISTED THE DRIVER.  THEY ACCEPTED THE HIS CLEANUP MATERIALS FOR DISPOSAL.  BOTH THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE SECURED TO A PALLET AND TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S  NEARBY FACILITY TO BE HELD FOR THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

DRIVER CALLED FROM A TRUCK STOP SHORTLY AFTER LEAVING THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.  THE FILL BUNG OF A DRUM AT THE END OF THE TRAILER HAS BLOWN OFF. SOME PRODUCT HAS ESCAPED ONTO THE FLOOR AND A SMALL QUANTITY DRIPPED ONTO THE MUD FLAPS.  DRIVER USED EQUIPMENT AND MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CLEAN THE DRUM HEAD, REPLACE THE BUNG AND SECURE IT IN PLACE WITH DUCT TAPE.  HE DID NOT HAVE A BUNG WRENCH TO PROPERLY TIGHTEN THE BUNG.  HE RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO HAVE THE IT TIGHTENED, THE WHOLE SHIPMENT INSPECTED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR CLEANED.  ON REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER, AS LONG AS THE PACKAGES WERE RENDERED SAFE FOR TRANSPORTATION, THEY SHOULD BE CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  SHIPMENT CONTINUED AND DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP, SMELLED AND SAW MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE MATERIAL IS QUITE THICK AND IS NOT LIKELY TO ESCAPE FROM THE TRAILER. HOWEVER, OTHER CONSIGNEE WILL NOT BE ABLE TO MAKE ENTRY TO ACCESS THEIR SHIPMENTS. CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO PLACE ABSORBENT/DAMMING MATERIAL AROUND THE DOOR AND EXPOSED SIDES OF THE TRAILER AND PROCEED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. WHEN DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY THE DOCK OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR REPORTED THAT THE FUMES WERE TOO STRONG TO ALLOW ANYONE TO ENTER THE TRAILER. THE CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN RETAINED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR FOR ASSISTANCE TO OVERPACK THE DRUM AND CLEAN UP THE TRAILER. WHEN THE CONTRACTOR'S SUPERVISOR ARRIVED HE ASSESSED THE LOAD AND REPORT THAT A CHOCK THAT HAD BEEN SET BEHIND THE DRUMS HAD BEEN PUSHED INTO THE DRUM. A PROTRUDING NAIL PUNCTURED THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS HAD BEEN LOST. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND ONE (1) DRUM OF SPILL ABSORBENT WAS GENERATED. BOTH DRUMS WERE LEFT AT THE FACILITY. THE SPILL CLEAN-UP ABSORBENT DRUM WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL.

DRIVER REPORTS THAT THERE IS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AROUND THE BUNG AND DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF THIS SINGLE SHIPMENT. THERE IS ALSO A VERY STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER. CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO SAID THAT THE LEAKAGE IS NOT AN UNUSUAL OCCURRENCE. THE DRUMS ARE VENTED BECAUSE THIS PRODUCT IS GIVEN TO PRESSURE BUILD UP. AS A RESULT THERE IS OCCASIONAL LEAKAGE THROUGH THE VENTS. THE DRIVER'S NEXT STOP IS IN CORTLAND, N.Y., ABOUT 40 MILES DISTANT. THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR AND ARRANGED TO HAVE THEM PROVIDE ONE TECHNICIAN TO MEET THE DRIVER AT THAT STOP. THE CONTRACTOR'S TECHNICIAN ARRIVED WITH A PLASTIC SALVAGE DRUM AT THE SAME TIME AS THE CARRIER'S VEHICLE. THE TECHNICIAN OVERPACKED THE VENTING DRUM WITH THE DRIVER'S ASSISTANCE. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CHECKED FOR SPILLED PRODUCT. AT THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST, THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM LATER IN THE DAY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. WE ARE AWARE THAT THE RELIEVING OF PRESSURE BUILD UP IS NORMAL AND NECESSARY BUT WE DO NOT AGREE THAT THIS NECESSITATES A CONCURRENT SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT.

column168: THE DISCHARGE OCCURRED ON JULY 2,2000 6:00 PM WHEN A PETTIT OIL COMPANY TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER INTO THE DITCH ON THE WEST SIDE OF HIGHWAY 101 ON ROUTE TO DELIVER TO CUSTOMER IN LONG BEACH, WASHINGTON. IT DAMAGES THE FRONT COMPARTMENT TO THE CARGO TANK ON THE TRUCK. THE ACCIDENT APPEARS TO HAVE RESULTED FROM A PROBLEM WITH THE NEW (2000 YR TRUCK, 2 MONTHS OLD) SUSPENSION SYSTEM. UNLOADED REGULAR GASOLINE LEAKED FROM THE FRONT TANK, AND FLOWED INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH AND THEN SUBSEQUENTLY FLOWED INTO THE UNNAMED TRIBUTARY OF FRESHWATER CREEK THAT WAS DRY AT THE TIME. IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT THE DRIVER CALLED 911 AND HIS TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR. WHO IN TURN CALLED PRESIDENT OF PETTIT OIL AND SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE MANAGER TO ACTIVATE PETTIT OIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. BY TIME PETTIT OIL COMPANY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED, THE WASHINGTON STATE POLICE, THE SOUTH BEND FIRE DEPART AND WASHINGTON STATE DOT WERE ON SITE. INJURED DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL IN SOUTH BEND WASHINGTON FOR BRUISED RIBS, SORENESS AND THEN RELEASED. AT THIS TIME WE BEGAN THE NOTIFICATION TO WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY WHO WAS ALREADY NOTIFIED BY 911 AND WERE IN ROUTE, UNITED STATES COAST GUARD PORTLAND OREGON AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. IN ROUTE TO ACCIDENT IT WAS DECIDED TO BRING IN OUR THIRD PARTY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP SPILL SITE. PRIOR TO FOSS SHOWING UP ON SITE PETTIT OIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM STARTED CONTAINMENT, REMOVING PRODUCT THAT WAS STILL IN THE TRUCK AND REMOVING TRUCK FROM CRASH SITE AND DITCH. BY THE NEXT MORNING WE NOTIFY ASSOCIATED EARTH SCIENCES PETTIT OIL COMPANY THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR (HYDRO GEOLOGIST AND GEOLOGIST) TO SUPERVISE CLEAN UP AND RESTORE ANY CONTAMINATED SOIL AND SUPERVISE AND REPORTING NEEDS FOR U.S. DOE AND WASHINGTON STATE DOE. ACTIONS TAKEN BY PETTIT OIL COMPANY TO PREVENT FUTURE SIMILAR DISCHARGES INCLUDE CHECKING ALL TRUCK AIR SUSPENSION SYSTEMS FOR PROPER ADJUSTMENT, AND CHECKING ALL TRUCK AND TRAILERS COMBINATIONS FOR PROPER ALIGNMENT. PETTIT OIL HAS WORKED WITH TRUCK'S MANUFACTURER/VENDER TO DETERMINE THE NATURE OF THE PROBLEM AND IDENTIFY MEASURES THAT COULD POTENTIALLY PREVENT SIMILAR PROBLEMS. ALL PETTIT OIL TRUCK WITH SIMILAR TRUCK SUSPENSION SYSTEMS HAVE BEEN CHANGED OR UPDATED.

OUR TRUCK ARRIVED AT DESTINATION SAFELY, WHILE UNLOADING PRODUCT(DIESEL FUEL) A CLAMP BROKE AND A SLIGHT SPRAY OF PRODUCT NEAR THE PUMP DEVELOPED. THIS SPRAY WAS NOTICED BY THE DRIVER WHEN IT APPEARDED ON THE DOCK BELOW THE TRUCK. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND GOT SOME ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO SOAK UP THE LEAK. BEFORE HE COULD GET THE ABSORBENT SOME DIESEL FUEL GOT INTO THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER (APX 1 GALLON). I CALLED NATIONAL RESPONSE#, AND THE COAST GUARD CAME OUT TO INSPECT, ALL THAT WAS VISIBLE WAS A SLIGHT SHEEN APX. 3 FT WIDE X 6 FT LONG. THEY INVESTIGATED AND NO FURTHER ACTION WAS TAKEN. ATTACHED IS A COPY OF COAST GUARD INCIDENT PAPER. STATE POLICE #00-04115(REPORT # ISSUED AFTER CALLING)

column168: DPC TRAILER CAUGHT ON FIRE WHILE MAKING DELIVERIES.  OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO QUENCH FIRE WITH EXTINGUISHER, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE FIRE RE-IGNITES CAUSING THE FUSE PLUGS ON (3) TON CONTAINERS TO MELT.  DPS WAS CLEARING AN AUTO ACCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION AND CONTACTED 9-1-1 OF THE FIRE.  DPS CLOSES THE ROADS TO TRAFFIC AND EVACUATES NEARBY BUSINESSES AND RESIDENCES.  LIBERTY HILL VFD RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE.  THE DPC DRIVER NOTIFIED CLEBURNE OFFICE AND RESPONSE TEAM WAS SENT.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE TEAM DONNED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GEAR.  THEY REPLACED FUSE PLUGS ON (3) TON CONTAINERS.  ALL TON CONTAINERS WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR TRANSPORT TO DPC FACILITY.  THE DAMAGED TRAILER WAS TOWED AWAY AND HIGHWAY WAS OPENED FOR TRAFFIC.  THE INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT FRICTION CAUSED BY A FLAT TIRE CAUSED THE FIRE ON THE TRAILER WHICH MELTED THE FUSE PLUGS CAUSING THE RELEASE OF CHLORINE.

ON 7/3/00 AT 0132 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OH 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND PAUL SCHMIDT, AS WELL AS, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES,  DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING A FUEL TYPE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA, OPENED THE  PACKAGE, AND BEGAN THE INSPECTION.  THEY OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND FOUND IT TO CONTAIN A STEEL DRUM.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THIS DRUM, THEY FOUND IT TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT AROUND THE CLOSURE.  THIS HAD A BUNG CLOSURE, AND HAD SEALANT BETWEEN THE PLUG AND THE DRUM.  HOWEVER, THE SEALANT DID NOT COMPLETELY SURROUND THE PLUG, LEAVING A SMALL OPENING, TO WHICH THE LEAK OCCURRED.  THIS WAS THE ONLY ITEM IN THIS FIBERBOARD BOX.  THEY REPLACED THE STEEL DRUM INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INSIDE OF 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED THE RECOVERY DRUM ONTO ITS DESTINATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND SHE RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED FOR THIS EMPLOYEE.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

column168: ON JULY 25, 2000 A APPROXIMATELY 1615 HRS. GATX 90218 WS DISCOVERED IN TRACK 1 1 OF THE TRRA Madison YARD TO HAVE A LIQUID MATERIAL ON THE OUTER JACKET OF THE TANK CAR. THE AREA IN QUESTION ALSO HAD A SHARP ODOR. SINCE FLAMMABLE CLASS 3 PLACARDS DISPLAYED THE ABOVE WAS REPORTED TO THE YARD MASTER. INSPECTION OF VALVE ARRANGEMENT LOCATED UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER BY 1ST RESPONDER SHOWED A LEAK FROM THE THREADS OF THE UNLOADING VALVE PLUG. ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO TIGHTEN THE PLUG IN QUESTION WHICH DID HAVE SOME SUCCEED IN SLOWING THE LEAD BUT WEEPING OF THE MATERIAL CONTINUED AROUND THE THREADS OF THE PLUG. CHEM-TREK WAS NOTIFIED AT 1740 HRS. OF THE INCIDENT WITH ROHM AND HAAS REPRESENTATIVE CONTACTING TRRA AT 1810 HRS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1930 HRS . TRRA WAS NOTIFIED THA ROHM AND HAAS HAD EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM IN ROUTE TO VENICE, ILLINOIS, FROM Louisville, Kentucky, ARRIVAL EST. 0300 HRS. JULY 26,2000 . FURTHER INSPECTION INDICATED AS TEMPERATURES DROPPED THE MATERIAL WAS NO LONGER WEEPING. THE VALVE PLUG WAS WRAPPED WITH HAZMAT ABSORBENT PADS AND CAR MOVE TO ISOLATED AREA. ROHM AND HAAS RESPONDER ARRIVED AT 0330HRS. ON JULY 26, 2000 WITH THE FOLLOWING DONE, VALVE AND PLUG WAS EXAMINED AND DISCOVERED THAT NO TEFLON TAPE HAD BEEN PLACED ON THREADS OF PLUG OUTRAGE OF TANK CAR WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE EXEPTABLE. PLUG HAD TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO PLUG AND PLUG REPLACED IN UNLOADING VALVE. INSPECTION REVEALED NO OTHER DEFECTS IN VALVE ARRANGEMENT. CAR RELEASED AT 0415HRS. JULY 26, 2000 FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION. CHEM-TREK INC # 07252000-086, 11 COMMERCE COMMISSION NOTIFIED 1900 HRS JULY 25, 2000 INC # 20001399. REMEDIATION OF SOIL IN AREA OF LEAKAGE TRK. # 11 WILL BE COMPLETED AT A LATER DATE.

FILE 2061 D, SHIPPER: CBS BEAUTY SUPPLY, AWB # MRR8200085051 RTP. ON 07/10/00 AT 0515 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING "D" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN JEFFREY KIDDER DONNED PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR.  HE OPENED THE BOX AND BEGAN HIS INSPECTION.  UPON THIS INSPECTION HE FOUND A YELLOW PIECE OF PAPER, SOME KIND OF NOTE, WHICH WAS NOT LEGIBLE DUE TO THE PRODUCT BEING SPILLED UPON IT.  HE ALSO FOUND THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEM: 5 X .5 OUNCE GLASS BOTTLES CONTAINING FINGER NAIL POLISH.  TWO OF THESE BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING WITH BROKEN CLOSURES.  THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS.  THIS WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. HE PLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PIECED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE OF TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  HE PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INSIDE A PLASTIC SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED THE DRUM IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0640.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE INNER CLOSURES OF THE METAL CANS. THE PACKAGE ALSO DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH IT. THE SPILL AGENT THAT INSPECTED THE CONTENTS, NOTIFIED ME OF THE SPILL. I ASKED THAT A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THE PRODUCT BE OBTAINED. WHEN THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THIS PRODUCT HAD A 100 DEGREE FARENHEIT FLASH POINT. I THEN NOTIFIED KATE ZAMPARELLI IN THE NE REGION COORDINATOR FAA OFFICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT, AND SOMEONE IN THE BOS/CASFO WAS TO INVESTIGATE.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES OCCURRED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION. SOME SPILLED MATERIAL HAD DRIED ON THE FLOOR (CONCRETE) OF THE WAREHOUSE AND COULD NOT BE CLEANED  UP. WHEN THE MANUFACTURER WAS CONTACTED FOR ADDITIONAL SPILL CLEANUP INSTRUCTIONS ON THE MSDS THEY RECOMMENDED THAT IT BE SCRAPED UP OFF THE CONCRETE. AN OUTSIDE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO DO SO. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AS IT WAS AN RQ SPILL MR. CREWS WAS THE EMPLOYEE AT THE RESPONSE CENTER AT (800) 424-8802 IT WAS CALLED IN TO MEET EPA REQUIRED REPORTING. THE CROSS REFERENCE FILE ON THIS FROM ON THEIR POINT OF VIEW IS REPORT # 536867. THERE WERE NO PACKAGE DISCREPANCIES ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT.

FILE: 3008 D, SHIPPER: CRESCENT CHEMICAL CO., AWB#ISP 1008682021 ISP (RETURN TO SHIPPER). ON 07/28/2000 AT 0235, A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington,  OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ TECHNICIANS CHRISTOPHOR CHAPPPA AND BRUCO SHILTZ, ALONG WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TAMARA A. RAMIREZ, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE  EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE OF THE TWO BOTTLES WAS FOUND TO BE BROKEN AND LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  EACH BOTTLE WAS INSIDE A  ZIPLOCK BAG.  THE BOTTLES WERE SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS.  THE OUTER PACKAGE SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE BOTTOM HALF OF THE BOX AND OBSCURING ANY MARKINGS ON THE BOTTOM.  THE BOTTLES WERE FOUND TO BE ISOPROPANOL.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED IT TO THE SHIPPER. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE SPILL WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF SCENE 0248.

column168: EMG MANAGER, MITCH DUGGER WAS ADVISED BY RMCC AT 14:55 HOURS OF A DERAILMENT AT THE UPLAND PAPERBOARD COMPANY AT ONTARIO, CA.  TANK CAR ACFX 79387 DERAILED WITH A 30 DEGREE LIST AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE CAR AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON PER MINUTE.  TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL (CONTRACTOR) WAS CALLED TO RESPOND.  THE LIQUID LINE VALVE HANDLE HAD BEEN POSITIONED OVER THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, CAUSING IT TO RELEASE PRODUCT. AFTER THE CAR WAS SEALED, IT WAS RERAILED WITHOUT ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

MGR. WILDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE MYO AT YARD CENTER THAT A CREW HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS YARD, YARD 2, TRACK 17.  MGR. WILDER CALLED RMCC. MGR WILDER INSTRUCTED THE MYO TO CALL RHODIA AND REQUEST THEIR DART TEAM RESPOND.  THE PLANT IS WITHIN 1/2 MILE OF THE SPILL SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL MGR. WILDER MEET WITH RHODIA SAFETY COORDINATOR, KURT HUDSPETH AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETE.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A LOOSE DIP WELL TUBE CAP, WHICH WAS ONLY FINGER TIGHT.  THE CAP WAS SECURED.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY THE DART TEAM.  CLEANING PADS WERE REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RHODIA PLANT.  NO WATERWAYS, DRAINS EFFECTED.  NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND, BUT DART TEAM ADVISED THAT THIS CAR HAD APPARENTLY BEEN LEAKING PRIOR TO ARRIVAL CHICAGO.  DART TEAM ADVISED THEY WILL CONTACT SHIPPER REGARDING SECUREMENT CHECKS PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.

REGIONAL MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, TIM O'BRIEN, RECEIVED A CALL FROM RMCC INDICATING LEAKING CAR GATX14586.  O'BRIEN RESPONDED, MET WITH HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THEN INSPECTED THE CAR.  HE FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD DISCHARGED SOME PRODUCT.  HE INSPECTED THE VALVE AND FOUND DETERIORATED O-RING.  O'BRIEN APPLIED EPOXY TO O-RING AND RE-SEATED.  HE ALSO TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER. MERISOL (SHIPPER) HAD GATX REPLACE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AT SETTEGAST YARD ON 7 -10 - 00.  AIR MONITORING DURING INCIDENT INDICATED 1 PPM IN AIR.

MR MIKE SEABAUGH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, CONTACTED MR JOHN STEWART, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, AT 610 HOURS 7/21/00 REGARDING A LEAKING TANK CAR, GATX 83476 IN TRACK 207 AT NORTH LITTLE ROCK.  MR STUART WILLIAMSON, TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR, PROVIDED WAYBILL INFORMATION AND THE LOCATION OF THE CAR WITHIN TRACK 207.  MR STEWART INSPECTED THE CAR FINDING THAT IT WAS VENTING ABNORMALLY FROM VALVING WITHIN THE VALVE HOUSING.  THE ENTIRE HOUSING WAS FILLED WITH FROST.  IN CONVERSING WITH MR SEABAUGH, IT WAS DECIDED TO ISOLATE THE CAR AT THE FREIGHT HOUSE FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  MR STEWART CONTACTED THE SHIPPER MR GLEN SPRINGFIELD, FARMLAND, 800-259-8095,  TO COMMUNICATE STATUS OF CAR.  AT 0930 HOURS 7/21/00, MR SEABAUGH AND MR STEWART FOUND THE A AND B END LIQUID EDUCTION LINE PLUGS WERE SETTING IN THE HOUSING NOT SECURE AND THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVES HAD VIBRATED OPEN.  THE PLUGS WERE SECURED AND THE VALVES TIGHTENED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT 1030 HOURS 7/21/00.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE THAT LED TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED. THE CONTAINER EXHIBITED A 'JET-A' LABEL AND WAS A FUEL SAMPLE BEING SENT FOR TESTING.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER FACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. PERSONNEL REPORTED THE ODOR OF PAINT THINNER.  THE SPRAYER WAS REMOVED, FLUID CLEANED, AND AIRCRAFT CLEARED BY MAINTENANCE RESULTING IN A 14 MINUTE DEPARTURE DELAY, SAN JOSE FIRE DEPT. THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE PROVO YARD 46, TRACK 6, AT THE EAST END. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY SCRUBBED THE WHITE VAPOR INTO A FIVE GALLON BOTTLE OF WATER. THE PRESSURE ON THE TANK CAR WAS LOWERED AND THE VALVE SHUT OFF AUTOMATICALLY. ED HURST, MGR, COMPLIANCE MEASURES WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE SPARKS, NV. INTERMODAL RAMP. MR. HURST CONTACTED UNIVERSAL ENVIRONMENTAL IN RENO, NV., (ROB PELHAM) AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND TO THE LOCATION AND INSPECT THE TRAILER. THE INSPECTION REVEALED THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED AND NONE OF THE PACKAGES WERE BREACHED. THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A LOOSE DRUM BUNG AND LIQUID EXPANSION DUE TO HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURE IN THE TRAILER. ALL BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE TRAILER ALLOWED TO  " AIR OUT".

column168: ON JULY 15, 2000, MARK VII TRANSPORTATION DELIVERED CONTAINER EMHU 233132 TO THE INTERMODAL RAMP AT DUPO, II. FOR RAIL TRANSPORTATION TO PHOENIX, AZ. ON JULY 27, 2000, THIS CONTAINER WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT THE PHOENIX RAMP. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER DUE TO THE TY-GUARD SECUREMENT COMING LOOSE ON THE RIGHT SIDE WALL. THIS SHIFTED LOAD CAUSED FOUR (4) 12.5 POUND POLY DRUMS TO SPILT ALLOWING THE DRY PRODUCT TO COME IN CONTACT WITH THE AIR AND CONDENSATION WITHIN THE CONTAINER. EACH PALLET HAD TO BE REWORKED AND THE DAMAGED PAILS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM. THE CONTAINER WAS WASHED DOWN WITH A SODIUM BICARBONATE SOLUTION AND WATER. THE PRODUCT WAS RELOADED INTO CONTAINER EMHU 684188. BOTH CONTAINERS   WERE RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION. CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT APPEARS TO BE FROM IMPROPER LOADING AND BRACING TO HOLD 37,371 POUNDS FROM SHIFTING IN RAIL TRANSPORTATION. PRODUCT WAS PRODUCED BY OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL, LOADED BY A WAREHOUSE CONTRACTOR OF OCCIDENTAL AND TRANSPORTED TO AND FROM THE RAIL RAMP BY MARK VII TRANSPORTATION ( CONTRACT HAULER FOR OCCIDENTAL).

RMCC REPORTED A SANTA FE TANK CAR SPOTTED ON THE RIP TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP. INSPECTION REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR RIP TRACK REPAIR.

column168: MITCH DUGGER, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, REPORTED TANKCAR TEIX 20523 LEAKED PRODUCT FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AT THE EAST TRACK 308, DEPARTURE YARD, NEAR THE PEPPER STREET OVERPASS. THERE WERE SOME VAPOR ODORS. AN AIR QUALITY TEST WAS PERFORMED AND THE AIR TESTED ACCEPTABLE. CHEMTREC, STATE, AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATION WERE MADE. GATX AND SAN BERNADINO COUNTY DISPATCHED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE. MR DUGGER HAD THE TANKCAR MOVED TO THE EAST END OF TRACK 120 IN COLTON YARD, PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL. AFTER AN INSPECTION BY RESPONSE PERSONNEL, THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

DURING THE PROCESS OF ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT THE ALTON & SOUTHERN RR YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, ILLINOIS, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICHARD TUFTS NOTED THAT THERE WAS A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE SECUREMENT FLANG OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AT THE PRESSURE PLATE SECUREMENT. MANAGER TUFTS INSPECTED ALL THE SECUREMENT BOLTS FOR ALL OF THE VALVES AND DETERMINED THAT ALL WERE LOOSE TO SOME EXTENT AND THAT AT LEAST TWO NUTS WERE APPROXIMATELY 1- 1& 1/2 TURNS LOOSE ON EACH OF THE VALVES. ADDITIONALLY, ALL VALVE PLUGS WERE LOOSE  AND ALL PACKING GLAND NUTS ON THE VALVE STEMS WERE VERY LOOSE. MANAGER TUFTS TIGHTENED ALL NUTS AND STILL WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE SLIGHT HISSING SOUND NOTED. A SECOND ATTEMPT AT TIGHTENING THE NUTS WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT SUCCESS IN STOPPING THE HISSING. THERE WAS A FAINT ODOR OF CHLORINE PRESENT IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING HOWEVER THERE WAS ONLY A MINIMAL VAPOR RELEASE OCCURRING. MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED THE RMCC DISPATCHER TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED THE DISPATCHER TO MAKE APPROPRIATE STATE AND FEDERAL REPORTS AND TO CONTACT CHEMTREC TO OBTAIN ASSISTANCE IN SHIPPER NOTIFICATION. MANAGER TUFTS DETERMINED THAT SINCE THE HISSING SOUND WAS STILL PRESENT AFTER ALL SECUREMENT EFFORTS, A "C" KIT WOULD HAVE TO BE APPLIED TO SECURE THE CAR. MANAGER TUFTS WAS CONTACTED BY MR. DAEN SAYLOR FROM PIONEER AMERICAS, INC. IN HENDERSON, NEVADA, REVERSE MOVE CONSIGNEE, 702-564-0206 OFFICE AND 702-523-3617  CELLULAR AND ADVISED MR. SAYLOR AS TO THE CURRENT SITUATION. MAR. SAYLOR AGREED WITH MANAGER TUFTS RECOMMENDATION TO BRING IN HULCHER SERVICES TO ASSIST IN MITIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT. MR. SAYLOR ALSO ADVISED THAT HE WOULD MAKE CONTACT WITH HIS COMPANY'S RESPONSE TEAM. MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED HULCHER SERVICES AND REQUESTED THAT THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPOND WITH A "C" KIT TO ASSIST IN THIS INCIDENT. CHLOREP, WESTLAKE SECTOR #13, MR. FRANK SOLOMANS 270-841-6515 WAS CONTACTED WITH THE  ASSISTANCE OF CHEMTREC AND THE SITUATION WAS DISCUSSED THOROUGHLY. MANAGER TUFTS RETURNED TO THE CAR AND ATTEMPTED TO DETERMINE THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE HISSING SOUND USING AMMONIA AS AN INDICATOR METHOD. AT THAT TIME, MANAGER TUFTS FELT THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF VAPOR PASSING THE GASKET BENEATH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED. ATTEMPTS TO RESEAT THE VALVE FAILED AND UPON ARRIVAL OF THE HULCHER CREW, A "C" KIT WAS APPLIED AND AN EFFECTIVE SEAL WAS ACCOMPLISHED. WORKING WITH THE HULCHER CREW AND WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF CHLOREP, MANAGER TUFTS ATTEMPTED TO LOCATE A SUPPLIER OF 20% CAUSTIC SOLUTION AND A TRANSPORT TRAILER IN ORDER TO DEPRESSURIZE THE TANK CAR WHICH CONTAINED 170PSI. ATTEMPTS TO SECURE A TRAILER WITH 20% CAUSTIC SOLUTION WERE UNSUCCESSFUL AND  AT APPROXMIMATELY, 0900 HRS ON 07/25/00, REPRESENTATIVES OF VERTEX CHEMICAL AT DUPO ADVISED THAT IF THE CAR COULD BE BROUGHT TO THEM, THEY WOULD ALLOW OFF LOADING AT THEIR FACILITY AND THAT THEY WOULD BE ABL

ON 7/18/00 AT 1954HRS, BILL SHAFFER, WICHITA YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 83656 WAS VENTING WHEN IN MOTION. MR. SHAFFER REPORTED YARD PERSONNEL COULD HEAR THE TANKCAR SLOSHING AND THE TANKCAR HAD AN ODOR AROUND IT WHEN IT WAS MOVED. HOWEVER, NO VISIBLE LEAK WAS OBSERVED. THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED IN YARD 1 TRACK 16. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED REPRESENTATIVES TO THE SCENE. CHEMTREC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. LANE SEKAVEC, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, ALONG WITH A REPRESENTATIVE FROM HAZMAT RESPONSE INC. (CONTRACTOR) IN WICHITA  ALSO RESPONDED. AT 0228HRS, AN INSPECTION BY RESPONDING PERSONNEL  REVEALED THAT THE RELEASE WAS FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE TOP OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED AND THE O RINGS WERE REPLACED. THE SCENE WAS SECURED FOR THE NIGHT, WITH  A  PARTIAL TRANSLOAD TO BE CONDUCTED IN THE MORNING. THE TRANSLOAD WAS BEGUN APPROXIMATELY 1215HRS AND WAS COMPLETED AT 1345 HRS. THE CAR WAS RELEASEDTO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

WHILE DOING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTION IN AT NEFF YARD, MGR CTS, LANE SEKOVEC, OBSERVED TANKCAR GATX 97170 LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT. THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMING FROM BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE FOR THE MANWAY AND THE TANK CAR NOZZLE. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO A MORE REMOTE LOCATION IN THE YARD PENDING A TRANSFER. THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE BOTH CONTACTED TO DETERMINE A COURSE OF ACTION AND ADVISE THEM OF THE SITUATION WITH THE CAR. THE TRANSFER PROCESS WAS BEGUN ON 7/20/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HRS. CONTRACT PERSONNEL FROM HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, INC.  WERE ON HAND TO PERFORM THE TRANSFER INTO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA  TRANSPORT SEMI-TRAILERS SUPPLIED BY GIRTON PROPANE. THE TRANSFER WAS STARTED AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HRS AND THE FIRST LOAD WAS COMPLETED AT 1330 HRS. THE TRANSPORT RETURNED AT 1900 HRS WITH THE TRANSFER RESTARTING AT 1930 HRS. THE SECOND LOAD WAS COMPLETED AT 2045 HRS. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED FOR THE NIGHT AND ALL PERSONNEL CLEARED THE AREA AT 2100 HRS. AT 0830 HRS, 7/21/00, THE TRANSFER WAS RESTARTED WITH THE LOAD COMPLETED AT 1000 HRS. THE FINAL TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS STARTED AT 1530 HRS AND WAS COMPLETED AT 1715 HRS. A WATER TRUCK WAS USED TO SCRUB THE ANHYDROUS VAPORS THROUGH TO LOWER THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR. THE SCRUBBING OPERATION WAS STARTED AT APPROXIMATELY 2045 HRS AND COMPLETED AT 2245 HRS. AT THE START OF OPERATIONS THE PRESSURE WAS 110 PSI. AT 2025 HRS THE PRESSURE WAS 75 PSI AND THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE LEAK FROM THE UNDER THE PRESSURE PLATE. AT 2059 HRS, THE PRESSURE WAS 50 PSI WITH A PH READING OF 11. AT 2255 PM, THE PH WAS APPROXIMATELY 12, WITH A PRESSURE 20 PSI. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND WOULD BE RELEASED AFTER THE THE WEEKEND AND A FINAL PRESSURE VERIFICATION. ON 7/24/00  AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HRS, THE PRESSURE WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO STILL BE 20 PSI. AT THIS TIME, MGR SEKOVEC REMOVED THE LOCKS AND FLAGS PROTECTING THE CAR RELEASED THE CAR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AT 4:00 AM, THE OFFICER AT THE ECHO SCALE, NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER CLIMB INTO THE TRAILER AND GOT THE PRO # OFF OF THE TANK.  HE CALL DISPATCH AND SHE IDENTIFIED THE SUBSTANCE AND FOUND OUT THAT FLOOR DRY CAN BE USED TO CLEAN IT UP. THE SCALE OFFICER CALLED IN THE HAZ MAT CLEAN UP CREW.  TROOPER GARTH TUNE CALLED DISPATCH AND SHE CONFERENCE IN HER SUPERVISOR ROB MORTIMER AND THEY AGREED THAT THE SPILL WAS SO SMALL THAT  MOLERWAY EMPLOYEE WILL BE ALLOWED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  TROOPER GARTH TUNE IS WITH THE HAZ MAT CLEANUP TEAM.  HE TOLD US TO TAKE FLOOR DRY, SHOVEL, CONTAINER, BROOM, AND TOOLS.  ALSO, A FACE MASK AND CLOTHING.  THE EMPLOYEE SECURED THE TANK FOR TRAVEL, CLEAN UP THE FLOOR DRY INTO CONTAINER READY FOR TRAVEL, CLEANED UP THE GROUND AND GOT THE TRAILER READY FOR TRAVEL.  WE  MOVED THE TRAILER INTO THE SLC SERVICE CENTER AND TROOPER TUNE MET US THERE TO INSTRUCT US ON HOWTO CLEAN AND DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY.  MOLERWAY SUPPLIED ALL THE CLEANUP MATERIAL AND PERSONEL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE LID ON THE TANK WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED BY THE SHIPPER.

FILE: 2067 F & D, SHIPPER: PSC INDUSTRIES INC., AWB# ATL 2362578934 SDF.  ON 7/31/00 AT  148, A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN THE A STORAGE BARN OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN ELWOOD BOHL DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKED ON.  HE OPENED THIS FIBERBOARD BOX AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING REGULATED ITEMS:  12 X 7 OUNCE METAL SPRAY CANS, METER MIST, AEROSOL CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE AEROSOL, UNDER PRESSURE.  1 X 17 OUNCE METAL SPRAY CAN, SELIG STRIPT EASE, AEROSOL, CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE. ACCORDING TO MSDS PROPER SHIPPING NAME:  AEROSOL, FLAMMABLE, UN1950. 2 X1 PINT METAL CAN WITH PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE.  SELIG MUSCLE.  ACCORDING TO MSDS PROPER SHIPPING NAME:  FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (CONTAINS PETROLEUM DISTILLATES.  UN1993.  1 X 1 PINT METAL CAN WITH PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, SELIG RUBBERCOTE.  ACCORDING TO MSDS PROPER SHIPPING NAME: PAINT UN 1263.  1 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, THERE WAS TAPE AROUND THIS LID.  THERE WAS LEAKAGE FROM THIS AREA.  THE LID APPEARED TO BE BROKEN, CAUSING LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES.  THE OTHER ITEMS WERE MISCELLANEOUS NON REGULATED ITEMS.  HE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED AND NEUTRALIZED THE BOX, AND PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE BAGGED SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THE AREA THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS NOT AFFECTED BY THIS SPILL.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX ONLY.  THERE WERE NO EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  A COPY OF ALL MSDS'S WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0206.

PASSENGER CARRIED THIS OXYGEN UNIT THROUGH SECURITY AT NEWARK INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT. THE UNIT WAS PLACED IN THE OVERHEAD AT THE PASSENGER'S SEAT. A PASSENGER SITTING IN THE ROW BEHIND PASSENGER ZEILER REPORTING A "HISSING SOUND" TO THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT. WHEN THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT INVESTIGATED, SHE DISCOVERED THIS OXYGEN UNIT AND IMMEDIATELY REMOVED IT FROM THE OVERHEAD. THE CAPTAIN HAD IT THEN REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT. SEE THE ATTACHED (REPRODUCED) PHOTOGRAPH. NOTE: THE LABEL ON THE UNIT IS A CLASS 2 OXYGEN LABEL AND UN-1073 WAS ALSO ON THE UNIT. NO WHERE ON THE UNIT DID IT SHOW FORBIDDEN IN AIR TRAVEL. THIS INCIDENT IS A MAJOR CONCERN AND TWA HAS ISSUED A WORLD-WIDE BULLETIN TO OUR AIRPORTS SYSTEM-WIDE.
