column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY CRAIG NICKEN, MTIO,LATC, LOS ANGLES, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. DEVELOPED AN OUTSIDE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP THE CONTAINER WHEN HE NOTED A SMALL POOL ( LESS THAN ONE GALLON) OF LIQUID ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THE NOSE. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC AND LOCATED THE CONTAINER STILL IN THE PARKING STALL. THE PAVEMENT AREA WAS SECURED AND COVERED WITH ABSORBENT. THE TRAILER WAS 'DIAPERED' AND MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA FOR INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, IT WAS NOTED THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING USED TO SECURE THE LADING. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE LOCAL RELAY COORDINATOR FOR ROADWAY, WHO PROVIDED A VERBAL APPROVAL TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. UPON REMOVING ALL OF THE FREIGHT. LOCATED A FLOOR LOADED PALLET AT THE LEFT FRONT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. ONE OF THE POLY DRUMS AGAINST THE LEFT FRONT CORNER WAS LEAKING. WHEN THE PALLET WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, A PIECE OF THE CORNER SHEET METAL  WAS NOTED TO HAVE BEEN PEELED BACK. THE POLY DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED AGAINST THE TORN METAL, WHICH ABRADED THROUGH THE SIDE WALL OF THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE TRAILER WAS DECONED, AND THE FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL TRAILER. THE DAMAGED DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS . NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EASY YARD AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER ALONG TRACK #807.  THE CONTAINER HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE RAILCAR AND PLACED ONTO A CHASSIS.  PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE CENTER FLOOR AREA OF THE CONTAINER AND POOLING ON THE GROUND, CREATING A SPILL AREA APPROXIMATELY 8 FEET WIDE BY 20 FOOT LONG.  THE AREA WAS SECURED WHILE THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED, AND THEN ABSORBED FOR PLACEMENT INTO DRUMS. THE RESIDUE ON THE RAILCAR WAS ALSO CLEANED SO THE EQUIPMENT COULD BE REUSED FOR FUTURE LOADING.  THE CONTAINER WAS GROUNDED IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE DRUMS, AS THIS FACILITY HAS NO LOADING DOCK TO WORK FROM.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED TWO PIECES OF 2X6 LUMBER ACROSS THE REAR OF THE LADING AT THE DOORWAY.  THE LUMBER WAS AT FLOOR LEVEL AND PROVIDED LITTLE RESTRAINT FOR THE DRUMS.  THIRTY-SIX DRUMS WERE FLOOR LADED, AND HAD MOVED DURING TRANSIT.  FOUR ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE DOUBLE STACKED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, AND HELD IN PLACE WITH 2X6 LUMBER PLACED INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS OF THE CONTAINER.  THERE WAS NO BILEVEL SEPARATION BETWEEN THE TOP TIER AND FLOOR LOADED DRUMS.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED LOADING PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER BOE PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND WITH SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  THESE WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK CAME FROM THE DRUMS IN THE TOP TIER STACKED IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  TWO OF THE DRUMS HAD BOTTOM CHIME DAMAGE FROM ABRADING THE TOP CHIMES OF THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS.  THE DRUMS LOST ALL BUT A GALLON OF PRODUCT.  THE THIRD DRUM HAS DAMAGE TO THE TOP ROLLING HOOP FROM ABRADING THE ADJACENT DRUM, AND LOST APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE SHIPABLE DRUMS RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS ARE TO BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES,  AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK.  THE TANK WAS NOTED LEAKING BY A DRIVER WHO WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE UNIT UP FOR DELIVERY.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, INSPECTED THE TANK AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE REAR DISCHARGE VALVE.  THE CLOSURE CAP WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT, WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO BY PASS AT THE THREADS. PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE THREADS AT A RATE OF ONE DROP EVERY 2 MINUTES.  IT APPEARS THAT LESS THAN A GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  AS AMBIENT TEMPERATURES WERE IN THE 80 DEGREE RANGE, THE PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATING AS IT HIT THE GROUND.  THE INTERNAL OPERATING HANDLE WAS OPENED AND CLOSED SEVERAL TIMES TO RESEAT THE VALVE.  WHILE THIS OPERATION APPEARED TO STOP THE LEAK, THERE WAS SOME CONCERN THAT THE VALVE MAY LEAK DURING THE REMAINDER OF THE TRIP ONTO DESTINATION.  APL WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER,  TABY AMERICA, WHO STATED THEY PROVIDED THE IM TANK FOR HOECHST CELANSES TO LOAD OUT OF TEXAS.  TABY HAD THEIR LOCAL REPRESENTATIVE, VENTURA LESBRO INSPECT THE TANK AND IT WAS DECIDED BY ALL PARTIES THAT THE TANK SHOULD BE TRANSLOADED.  TABY PROVIDED AN EMPTY TANK, TABU 224448, WHICH WAS DELIVED BY VENTURA LESBRO.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM HOECHST CELANESE ARRIVED ON SITE, AND THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS COMPLETED ON WEDNESDAY, JULY 26, 2000.  THE LEAKING TANK WILL BE INSPECTED BY VENTURA LESBRO,  AND  REPAIRED AS NECESSARY.  THE BILLING WAS CHANGED TO REFLECT THE NEW IM TANK,  AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR HANDLING.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ITS PERSONNEL REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  DEVELOPED A DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE CONTAINER UP FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD, INSPECTED THE CONTAINER, AND FOUND A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID <LESS THAN 1 PINT> ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE REAR DOOR. THE CONTAINER WAS GROUNDED TO FACILITATE THE REWORK OF THE LADING. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED SEVERAL PALLETS CONTAINING CARTONS AND 5 GALLON PAILS HAD TOPPLED.  THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT INTO THE VOID AT THE REAR OF  THE LADING.  DID AIR BAGS HAD BEEN USED TO COMPENSATE FOR VOID SPACES DOWN THE CENTER OF THE LADING, AND SEVERAL OF THE BAGS HAD BURST FROM THE MOVEMENT OF THE LADING AGAINST THEM.  CARTONS ON PALLETS, AND 5 GALLON PAILS ON PALLETS, WERE DOUBLE STACKED THROUGH OUT THE CONTAINER, AND NO BILEVEL SEPARATION WAS USED.  WHILE REMOVING THE TOPPLED LADING AT THE REAR, IT WAS NOTED THE 5 GALLON PAILS REMAINED INTACT.  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE CARTONS OF ABC FRESH PLUS, A HOSPITAL DISINFECTANT, SHIPPED AS A CONSUMER COMMODITY ORM-D.  THE MANUFACTURERS MSDS SHOWS THIS PRODUCT AS A DISINFECTANT, CORROSIVE LIQUID, UN 1903.  NUMEROUS CARTONS OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CRUSHED.  EACH CARTON CONTAINED 4 EACH 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES.  A TOTAL OF 21 BOTTLES WERE DAMAGE OR LEAKING, AND ALL WERE PLACED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR CONTAINMENT.  SEVERAL OTHER CARTONS CONTAINING 1 QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES OF A NON REGULATED ENZYME WERE ALSO DAMAGED AND CRUSHED.  THE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. ONCE THE FREIGHT WAS PROPERLY SECURED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.  THE DRUMS WITH THE DAMAGED BOTTLES ARE BEING HELD PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

DON YORK, SITE REMEDIATION MGR REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 95679 WAS VENTING FROM A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SHIPPER ( ATOFINA CHEMICAL INC. ) CONTACTED RESCAR TO RESPOND FROM THEIR CEDAR RAPIDS OFFICE.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS ON TRACK 705 YARD TWO AT CEDAR RAPIDS.  CEDAR RAPIDS FIRE DEPT AND LYNN CTY HAZMAT TEAM WERE ON SCENE.  MTO DAVE CRAWFORD STATED THE CAR WAS IN A SAVE AREA AND REPORTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR EVERY SIXTY SECONDS, FORMING A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD ABOUT THE TANKCAR APPROXIMATELY 1 TO 2 FEET IN DIAMETER.  LIQUID PRODUCT WAS ALSO LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANKCAR.  RESCAR PERSONEL REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC IN KIND AND SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS EFFECTED BY THIS SPILL.

DON YORK SITE REDEM MGR.  WAS CALLED BY THE CANEL ST INTERMODAL RAMP AND ADVISED THAT A TRAILER HAD ARRIVED AT THE RAMP LEAKING PRODUCT. YELLOW FREIGHT SYSTEM (SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE) RESPONDED WITH THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR AND DISCOVERED A FIVE GALLON CONTAINER LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE NEAR THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND CLEANED THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER.  NO SPILLED PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. UNION PACIFIC WAS NOT THE CARRIER AT THE TIME THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED.  HOWEVER, THIS REPORT IN BEING FILED IN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH REGULATORY REPORTING REQUIREMENT 49 CFR 171.16 (A).

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ITS PERSONNEL, EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  DEVELOPED A DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK THE CONTAINER UP FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE OBSERVED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THE MIDSHIP AREA.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YARD, INSPECTED THE CONTAINER, AND FOUND THE LIQUID WOULD BURN DURING A FIELD TEST, IF ASSISTED.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO A LOCATION WHERE IT COULD BE GROUNDED AND REWORKED.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS, OBSERVED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING TO CONSIST OF SEVERAL PIECES OF SCRAP LUMBER NAILED WITH NO OTHER RESTRAINT SYSTEM IN PLACE.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER BOE 6C FOR THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES FOR TRANSIT BY RAIL.  IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM(S) , THE LADING HAD TO BE REMOVED.  WHILE REMOVING THE LADING, IT WAS NOTED THAT NONE OF THE VARIOUS HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WERE PROPERLY STOWED, AND SEGRAGATION OF THE DRUMS WAS NON EXISTENT.  HALF WAY INTO THE CONTAINER, LOCATED A PALLET CONTAINING FOUR EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS, THAT HAD A PRODUCT TRAIL BENEATH IT.  ONCE THE PALLET WAS REMOVED, AND THE STRETCH WRAP CUT AWAY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE PALLET WAS USED, AND SEVERAL OF THE CROSS SLATS WERE BROKEN AWAY FROM THE OUTER EDGE OF THE PALLET, WHICH ALLOWED AN EXPOSED BENT OVER NAIL HEAD TO ABRADE THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM HAD A FLAMMABLE LABEL APPLIED, AND THE PRODUCT LABEL INDICATED THE MATERIAL WAS 'MINERAL SPIRITS, PARAFFIN WAX', A COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL.  THE DRUM HOWEVER, BORE NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  ONCE THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: UPON BREAKOUT IN THE AM AT THE NAG SERVICE CENTER, LARRY BUCHWITZ NOTICED THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER FLOOR AS WET. WHEN THE MOVED THE DRUM LIQUID CAME OUT FROM THE BOTTOM. WE CONTAINED THE LEAKING DRUM IN AN OVERPACK DRUM, CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH OIL DRY, PLACED THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY IN A 5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER AND NOTIFIED ALL OF THE PROPER CONTACTS

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT YERMO, CALIFORNIA.  DEVELOPED AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR, EXTRA TANK LINES, WAS LOADING JET FUEL INTO A THE ABOVE TANK CAR, WHICH CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  DURING THIS PROCESS, 2 EMPLOYEES OF EXTRA TANK LINES, WERE OVER COME WITH FUMES AND WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  THERE WAS A REPORTED LEAK, BUT IT WAS NOT KNOWN IF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE TANK CAR OR THE TANK TRUCKS.  A TRACK LIST SHOWED THE VARIOUS TANK CARS ON SPOT, HOWEVER, IT WAS NOT KNOWN WHICH CAR WAS INVOLVED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CLOSED OFF THE AREA AND WAS EVACUATING THE TOWN OF YERMO NEAR CALICO STREET AND YERMO ROAD.  MANAGER COOPER RAN ALL THE TANK CARS ON THE TRACK LIST, AND FOUND ONLY THE ABOVE CAR TO HAVE ANY PREVIOUS MOVES WITH THE ACID PRODUCT.  THE CAR NUMBER WAS SUPPLIED TO THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, HOW EVER, IT COULD NOT BE CONFIRMED AS THE CAR INVOLVED. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO YERMO, AND MET WITH ALL THE PARTIES INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT.  DEVELOPED EXTRA HAD LOADED 3 TRUCK LOADS OF THE JET FUEL INTO THE ABOVE TANK CAR WHEN THEY DISCOVERED THIS CAR WAS NOT ON THEIR LIST FOR LOADING.  AS THE CAR WAS OWNED BY JONES HAMILTON, A SALT LAKE REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE CODY GROUP CONTACTED JONES HAMILTON REQUESTING THE USE OF THE CAR TO TRANSPORT THE FUEL.  JONES HAMILTON ADVISED THE CODY GROUP THEY COULD NOT USE THE CAR AND WERE INSTRUCTED TO REMOVE THE FUEL. WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF REMOVING THE FUEL FROM THE TANK CAR, THE OPERATORS WERE ALSO REMOVING THE ESTIMATED 25 - 30 GALLON HEEL OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE ACID ATE THROUGH THE ALUMINUM PIPING ON THE TANK TRUCK AND RELEASED THE RESIDUE ACID AND FUEL ONTO THE GROUND BELOW THE TANK TRUCK.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 3000 GALLONS OF JET FUEL AND  LESS THAN 25 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC WAS RELEASED.  THE 2 EXTRA DRIVERS THAT WERE INVOLVED IN THE OFF LOADING, SHUT THE PUMP DOWN, AND DROVE THEMSELVES TO THE VICTOR VALLEY HOSPITAL.  ONCE EVERYTHING WAS SORTED OUT, A TEST OF THE LIQUID IN THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS COMPLETED WHICH SHOWED THE PH LEVEL TO BE AROUND 1.8. IT WAS ESTIMATED THE TANK CAR CONTAINED ROUGHLY 17,000 GALLONS OF JET FUEL MIXED WITH THE RESIDUE ACID.  IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE LIQUID FROM THE TANK AND TRANSPORT IT FOR DISPOSAL, THE PRODUCT HAD TO BE TREATED.  THE PH WAS LOW ENOUGH TO TRANSPORT IN A RUBBER LINED TRUCK, HOWEVER, THE JET FUEL WOULD ATTACK THE RUBBER LINING.  IF A STAINLESS TRUCK WERE TO BE USED TO TRANSPORT THE JET FUEL PORTION, THE ACID WOULD ATTACK THE METAL.  SODA ASH WAS BROUGHT IN, ADDED TO THE PRODUCT, AND DISPERSED WITH A MAKE SHIFT AIR WAND.  THIS BROUGHT THE PH LEVEL UP TO 5.  THE 2 ORIGINAL TANK TRUCKS WERE DECONED AND MOVED OFF THE SITE FOR CLEAN OUT.  EXCAVATION OF THE SPILL AREA BEGAN, AND ALL THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED INTO ROLL OFF BINS FOR STORAGE PENDING THE PROFILLING FOR DISPOSAL. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON JULY 24, BARRY WATKINS AND I WERE HEADING FROM MADRAS, OR TO THE HELIBASE JUST OUTSIDE FOSSIL, OR IN TRUCK 9 WITH TRAILER 115 AND PICKUP 19 IN TOW. WE WERE GOING ALONG HWY 218. WE CAME OVER THE TOP OF THE MOUNTAIN AND STARTED DOWN HILL AT ABOUT 35 MPH. THE ROAD WAS WINDING. AT AROUND 12:30 BARRY ASKED ME TO PULL OVER SO WE MIGHT CHECK THE MAP. AT THAT TIME I WAS DOING 40 MPH. I SAW A SHOULDER AND WENT TO PULL OFF. BUT THE BRAKES DID NOT SEEM TO GRAB MUCH. THEN I SAW PRESSURE GAUGE WAS ALMOST AT 60 PSI, THEN IT CAME ON. WE STILL CONTINUED DOWN MOUNTAIN TRYING TO SLOW DOWN AND STAY IN CONTROL. I DOWN SHIFTED AND ENGINE REDLINED AND AIR PRESSURE DID NOT BUILD. I CONTINUED TO STAB BRAKE. AT ABOUT 55-60 MPH THE PRESSURE DROPPED TO BELOW 30 PSI AND THE BRAKES CAME ON. I SAW SMOKE POURING OUT OF THE REAR WHEELS. I WAS LOSING CONTROL OF TRUCK. I CHOOSE TO GO LEFT INTO HILL RIGHT OVER RAVINE.  WE HIT MOUNTAIN THEN TRUCK CLIMBED ABOUT 40-45 FEET UP THE HILL WHERE IT STOPPED. THE PICKUP HAD UNCOUPLED. THE FUEL TRUCK CAME TO A STOP FOR A SECOND THEN IT ROLLED DOWN HILL 4 TIMES AND CAME TO REST AT SIDE OF ROAD. BARRY AND I ASSESSED THE TRUCK AND NOTICED FUEL AND NOTICED FUEL LEAKING AND SMOKE COMING OFF WHEELS. WE FLAGGED DOWN A GUY AND HE CALLED 911. THE TRUCK CONTAINED 1200 GALLONS OF JET A FUEL.
